#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:166
msgid "Pipeline mode usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:168
msgid ""
"Psycopg supports the pipeline mode via the `Connection.pipeline()` method. "
"The method is a context manager: entering the ``with`` block yields a "
"`Pipeline` object. At the end of block, the connection resumes the normal "
"operation mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:172
msgid ""
"Within the pipeline block, you can use normally one or more cursors to "
"execute several operations, using `Connection.execute()`, `Cursor.execute()` "
"and `~Cursor.executemany()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:176
msgid ""
">>> with conn.pipeline():\n"
"...     conn.execute(\"INSERT INTO mytable VALUES (%s)\", [\"hello\"])\n"
"...     with conn.cursor() as cur:\n"
"...         cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO othertable VALUES (%s)\", "
"[\"world\"])\n"
"...         cur.executemany(\n"
"...             \"INSERT INTO elsewhere VALUES (%s)\",\n"
"...             [(\"one\",), (\"two\",), (\"four\",)])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:186
msgid ""
"Unlike in normal mode, Psycopg will not wait for the server to receive the "
"result of each query; the client will receive results in batches when the "
"server flushes it output buffer. You can receive more than a single result "
"by using more than one cursor in the same pipeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:191
msgid ""
"If any statement encounters an error, the server aborts the current "
"transaction and will not execute any subsequent command in the queue until "
"the next :ref:`synchronization point <pipeline-sync>`; a `~errors."
"PipelineAborted` exception is raised for each such command. Query processing "
"resumes after the synchronization point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:199
msgid "Certain features are not available in pipeline mode, including:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:201
msgid "COPY is not supported in pipeline mode by PostgreSQL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:202
msgid ""
"`Cursor.stream()` doesn't make sense in pipeline mode (its job is the "
"opposite of batching!)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:204
msgid "`ServerCursor` are currently not implemented in pipeline mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:205
msgid ""
"You cannot execute :ref:`multiple statements in the same query <multi-"
"statements>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:210
msgid ""
"Starting from Psycopg 3.1, `~Cursor.executemany()` makes use internally of "
"the pipeline mode; as a consequence there is no need to handle a pipeline "
"block just to call `!executemany()` once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:218
msgid "Synchronization points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:220
msgid ""
"Flushing query results to the client can happen either when a "
"synchronization point is established by Psycopg:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:223
msgid "using the `Pipeline.sync()` method;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:224
msgid "on `Connection.commit()` or `~Connection.rollback()`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:225
msgid "at the end of a `!Pipeline` block;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:226
msgid "possibly when opening a nested `!Pipeline` block;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:227
msgid ""
"using a fetch method such as `Cursor.fetchone()` (which only flushes the "
"query but doesn't issue a Sync and doesn't reset a pipeline state error)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:230
msgid ""
"The server might perform a flush on its own initiative, for instance when "
"the output buffer is full."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:233
msgid ""
"Note that, even in :ref:`autocommit <autocommit>`, the server wraps the "
"statements sent in pipeline mode in an implicit transaction, which will be "
"only committed when the Sync is received. As such, a failure in a group of "
"statements will probably invalidate the effect of statements executed after "
"the previous Sync, and will propagate to the following Sync."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:239
msgid "For example, in the following block:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:241
msgid ""
">>> with psycopg.connect(autocommit=True) as conn:\n"
"...     with conn.pipeline() as p, conn.cursor() as cur:\n"
"...         try:\n"
"...             cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO mytable (data) VALUES (%s)\", "
"[\"one\"])\n"
"...             cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO no_such_table (data) VALUES "
"(%s)\", [\"two\"])\n"
"...             conn.execute(\"INSERT INTO mytable (data) VALUES (%s)\", "
"[\"three\"])\n"
"...             p.sync()\n"
"...         except psycopg.errors.UndefinedTable:\n"
"...             pass\n"
"...         cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO mytable (data) VALUES (%s)\", "
"[\"four\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:254
msgid ""
"there will be an error in the block, ``relation \"no_such_table\" does not "
"exist`` caused by the insert ``two``, but probably raised by the `!sync()` "
"call. At at the end of the block, the table will contain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:258
msgid ""
"=# SELECT * FROM mytable;\n"
"+----+------+\n"
"| id | data |\n"
"+----+------+\n"
"|  2 | four |\n"
"+----+------+\n"
"(1 row)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:268
msgid "because:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:270
msgid ""
"the value 1 of the sequence is consumed by the statement ``one``, but the "
"record discarded because of the error in the same implicit transaction;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:272
msgid ""
"the statement ``three`` is not executed because the pipeline is aborted (so "
"it doesn't consume a sequence item);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:274
msgid ""
"the statement ``four`` is executed with success after the Sync has "
"terminated the failed transaction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:279
msgid ""
"The exact Python statement where an exception caused by a server error is "
"raised is somewhat arbitrary: it depends on when the server flushes its "
"buffered result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:283
msgid ""
"If you want to make sure that a group of statements is applied atomically by "
"the server, do make use of transaction methods such as `~Connection."
"commit()` or `~Connection.transaction()`: these methods will also sync the "
"pipeline and raise an exception if there was any error in the commands "
"executed so far."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:291
msgid "The fine prints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:295
msgid "The Pipeline mode is an experimental feature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:297
msgid ""
"Its behaviour, especially around error conditions and concurrency, hasn't "
"been explored as much as the normal request-response messages pattern, and "
"its async nature makes it inherently more complex."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:301
msgid ""
"As we gain more experience and feedback (which is welcome), we might find "
"bugs and shortcomings forcing us to change the current interface or "
"behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/pipeline.rst:305
msgid ""
"The pipeline mode is available on any currently supported PostgreSQL "
"version, but, in order to make use of it, the client must use a libpq from "
"PostgreSQL 14 or higher. You can use the `~Capabilities.has_pipeline` "
"capability to make sure your client has the right library."
msgstr ""
